The power set of a set A is the set of all possible subsets of A, including the empty set and the set A itself. For a set with n elements, the cardinality (number of elements) of its power set is 2^n.

For the set A = {1, 2, 3}, we can list all the possible subsets:

1. {} (the empty set)
2. {1}
3. {2}
4. {3}
5. {1, 2}
6. {1, 3}
7. {2, 3}
8. {1, 2, 3}

So, the power set of A is P(A) = { {}, {1}, {2}, {3}, {1, 2}, {1, 3}, {2, 3}, {1, 2, 3} }.

The cardinality of set A is 3 (since it has 3 elements), and the cardinality of the power set P(A) is 8 (since it has 8 elements). 

To show that the cardinality of the power set is greater than the cardinality of the set A, we can compare their cardinalities:

Cardinality of P(A) = 2^n = 2^3 = 8
Cardinality of A = 3

Since 8 > 3, the cardinality of the power set P(A) is greater than the cardinality of the set A.
